T1  - Autonomy and Incentives in Chinese State Enterprises*
PY  - 1994
Y1  - 1994/02/01
DO  - 10.2307/2118432
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 109
IS  - 1
SP  - 183
EP  - 209
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - When the responsibility for output decisions was shifted from the state to the firm, and when firms were allowed to retain more of their profits, managers of Chinese state-owned enterprises strengthened workers' incentives. The managers paid more in bonuses and hired more workers on fixed-term contracts. The new incentives were effective: productivity increased with increases in bonus payments and in contract workers. The increase in autonomy raised workers' incomes (but not managers' incomes) and investment in the enterprise, but tended not to raise remittances to the state.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2118432
ER  - 



